{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015RBCU6ctHhmfQwUAzXna7f","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the data I need to write the paper trade analysis. Let me compile the analysis:\n\n**Paper Trade Summary:**\n- Total trades: 19 closed\n- Overall win rate: 26.32% (5 wins out of 19)\n- Total PnL: -$13.73\n- Best trade: +$2.22\n- Worst trade: -$6.20\n\n**By Strategy:**\n- mean_reversion: 11 trades, 2 wins, 8 losses, win rate 18.18%, total PnL -$16.97, avg -$1.54\n\n\n- momentum: 8 trades, 3 wins, 3 losses (2 breakeven), win rate 37.5%, total PnL +$3.24, avg +$0.41\n\nThe mean_reversion strategy is showing a dramatic collapse in paper trading compared to backtests—dropping from 85.7% to just 18.18% win rate. Meanwhile, momentum is actually outperforming in live trading at 37.5% despite being disabled due to poor backtest results, and I'm noticing some trades were executed with unusually low confidence scores.\n\nLooking at the confidence threshold enforcement, it seems the 0.80 minimum isn't being consistently applied across all trades. The worst mean_reversion loss came from ETHW with a -$6.20 drawdown, and when I examine the high-confidence mean_reversion trades, there's a wide spread in actual returns—some hitting the expected targets while others showing significant losses despite the confidence scores.\n\nNow I'm noticing that some recent mean_reversion trades have no confidence values recorded at all, and the momentum trades are consistently underperforming with confidence levels between 0.20 and 0.53, well below the threshold. Let me trace through the cumulative drawdown across the April 2nd trades to see where the largest peak-to-trough decline occurred.\n\nThe maximum drawdown hit -$13.73 by April 3rd. Looking at the actual trade exits versus entries, most losses seem to stem from adverse market movement rather than slippage—the backtest showed an 85.7% win rate for mean_reversion, but the live trading results are telling a different story.\n\nNow I'm calculating the actual slippage on individual trades by comparing entry and exit prices on the same contract, looking at cases where the market barely moved to isolate the slippage component from the strategy's directional performance.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1993,"cache_read_input_tokens":29055,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1993},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"64df335f-fbf4-4b27-b2e9-2dac2d59998c","uuid":"e22d29d8-0b57-4f5e-bdb3-a44308d12a0e"}
